attacks.expected_behavior: The command downloads a file from a URL and executes it, demonstrating user execution

attacks.description: Execute a malicious script
attacks.expected_behavior: The script will execute with the user's permissions, potentially performing malicious actions.

attacks.description: Download, make executable, and execute a malicious payload from a local web server
attacks.expected_behavior: The payload will be downloaded, made executable, and executed with the user's permissions, potentially performing malicious actions.

attacks.description: Encode a benign string into Base64, simulating a malicious payload.
attacks.expected_behavior: A file named 'encoded.txt' will be created in the %TEMP% directory containing the Base64 encoded string.

attacks.description: Decode the Base64 string and save it to a new file, simulating the execution of a malicious attachment.
attacks.expected_behavior: A file named 'decoded.txt' will be created in the %TEMP% directory containing the decoded string.

attacks.description: Open the decoded file with Notepad, simulating a user interacting with a malicious file.
attacks.expected_behavior: Notepad will open displaying the contents of the 'decoded.txt' file.

attacks.command: echo 'Phishing email content' | mail -s 'Test Email' user@example.com
attacks.description: Simulate a phishing email using the mail command
attacks.expected_behavior: An email with the specified content will be sent to the target user

attacks.description: Simulate a phishing request using curl
attacks.expected_behavior: A POST request with the specified data will be sent to the target URL

attacks.description: Simulate a phishing attack using wget and xdg-open
attacks.expected_behavior: The phishing HTML page will be downloaded and opened in the default browser

attacks.description: Basic example of masquerading by running a command that creates a file in the temp directory, mimicking a legitimate system operation.
attacks.expected_behavior: Creates a file named test.txt in the temp directory without displaying any command prompt windows.

attacks.description: Intermediate example that not only creates a file but also hides it, making it less detectable by casual observation.
attacks.expected_behavior: Creates a hidden file named test.txt in the temp directory.

attacks.description: Advanced example of masquerading where a legitimate system file (cmd.exe) is copied to a temporary location with a name that might appear legitimate, executed, and then deleted, leaving minimal traces.
attacks.expected_behavior: Creates a copy of cmd.exe in the temp directory with a different name, executes it, and then attempts to delete the copy.

attacks.description: Copy the ls command to the user's home directory and make it executable, potentially masquerading it as a different command.
attacks.expected_behavior: The command creates a copy of the ls command in the user's home directory and makes it executable.

attacks.description: Create a symbolic link named fake_script.sh that points to the bash executable, masquerading as a script.
attacks.expected_behavior: A symbolic link is created, making it appear as though there is a script named fake_script.sh when in reality it's a link to bash.

attacks.command: mv ~/legitimate_script.sh ~/system_script.sh; echo '#!/bin/bash' > ~/system_script.sh; echo 'echo "Masqueraded script executed"' >> ~/system_script.sh; chmod +x ~/system_script.sh
attacks.description: Rename a legitimate script to appear as a system script, then replace its contents with a simple bash script that prints a message when executed, demonstrating masquerading of scripts.
attacks.expected_behavior: The original script is renamed and overwritten with a new script that, when executed, prints 'Masqueraded script executed', demonstrating how a script can be masqueraded as a system script.

attacks.technique_name: Steal or Manipulate Other Credential Material
attacks.description: Display user accounts on the system, potentially identifying targets for credential theft.
attacks.expected_behavior: Lists local user accounts.

attacks.technique_name: Steal or Manipulate Other Credential Material
attacks.description: List stored credentials for the current user, directly related to manipulating credential material.
attacks.expected_behavior: Displays stored credentials.

attacks.technique_name: Steal or Manipulate Other Credential Material
attacks.description: Decode a base64-encoded string representing a credential, simulating credential material manipulation.
attacks.expected_behavior: Decodes the base64 string to a plaintext credential.

attacks.technique_name: Steal or Manipulate Other Credential Material
attacks.description: Search for password strings in /etc/ directory and subdirectories
attacks.expected_behavior: This command searches for lines containing the string 'password' in all files within the /etc/ directory and its subdirectories, potentially revealing credential information.

attacks.technique_name: Steal or Manipulate Other Credential Material
attacks.description: Display the contents of the passwd file
attacks.expected_behavior: This command displays the contents of the /etc/passwd file, which contains user account information but not passwords themselves, as they are stored in /etc/shadow.

attacks.technique_name: Steal or Manipulate Other Credential Material
attacks.description: Display the contents of the shadow file
attacks.expected_behavior: This command attempts to display the contents of the /etc/shadow file, which contains encrypted passwords. It requires admin privileges and poses a higher safety risk due to the sensitive nature of the information it accesses.

attacks.description: Add a new user to simulate actor-controlled account addition
attacks.expected_behavior: A new user 'testuser' is added to the system.

attacks.description: Create a new directory and grant access to the newly created user, simulating alternate authentication material usage
attacks.expected_behavior: A new directory is created in the temp folder, and the 'testuser' is granted modify access to it.

attacks.description: Execute a command under the context of the newly created user, demonstrating the use of alternate authentication material
attacks.expected_behavior: The command prompt displays the username of the 'testuser' when executed.

attacks.description: Attempt to login to a remote server using an alternate username
attacks.expected_behavior: The command attempts to establish an SSH connection to example.com with the username testuser. If the credentials are valid, it logs in; otherwise, it prompts for a password or fails.

attacks.description: Generate a new SSH key pair for potential use in alternate authentication
attacks.expected_behavior: This command generates a new RSA SSH key pair in the /tmp directory. It requires admin privileges because it's using sudo. The generated key could potentially be used for authentication to other systems.

attacks.description: Use curl to test HTTP authentication with alternate credentials
attacks.expected_behavior: This command attempts to access the HTTP authentication endpoint on example.com using the username testuser and password testpass. If the credentials are valid, it returns the protected content; otherwise, it returns an authentication error.

attacks.command: powershell -Command "$signature = @"[DllImport("user32.dll")] public static extern IntPtr GetDesktopWindow();"; Add-Type -MemberDefinition $signature -Name APISetDesktop -PassThru | Out-Null; $hwnd = [APISetDesktop]::GetDesktopWindow(); $signature = @"[DllImport("user32.dll")] public static extern bool PrintWindow(IntPtr hWnd, IntPtr hdcBlt, uint nFlags);"; Add-Type -MemberDefinition $signature -Name APISetDesktop -PassThru | Out-Null; [APISetDesktop]::PrintWindow($hwnd, [System.IntPtr]::Zero, 0); $bitmap = New-Object System.Drawing.Bitmap(100, 100); $graph = [System.Drawing.Graphics]::FromImage($bitmap); $graph.CopyFromScreen(100, 100, 0, 0, $bitmap.Size); $bitmap.Save("$env:TEMP\advanced_screenshot.png");"
attacks.description: Utilizes the Windows API through PowerShell to capture a portion of the screen and save it as a PNG file in the temporary directory.
attacks.expected_behavior: Saves a portion of the screen as a PNG file in the temporary directory.

attacks.description: Downloads a benign executable from a URL and executes it, simulating user execution of a malicious file.
attacks.expected_behavior: The benign executable will be downloaded and executed without any harmful effects.

attacks.command: powershell -Command "Start-Process -FilePath 'C:\\Windows\\System32\\notepad.exe' -ArgumentList '/c echo This is a test > %TEMP%\\test.txt'"
attacks.description: Uses PowerShell to start Notepad and create a text file in the temporary directory, simulating the execution of a malicious file with a benign payload.
attacks.expected_behavior: Notepad will start, and a text file named test.txt will be created in the temporary directory with the content 'This is a test'.

attacks.command: cmd.exe /c echo This is a test > %TEMP%\test.bat && %TEMP%\test.bat
attacks.description: Creates a batch file in the temporary directory and executes it, demonstrating user execution of a potentially malicious file.
attacks.expected_behavior: A batch file named test.bat will be created in the temporary directory, and its contents will be executed, displaying 'This is a test' in the command prompt.

attacks.description: Downloads a file, makes it executable, and runs it
attacks.expected_behavior: The command downloads a file, changes its permissions to executable, and then executes it. This demonstrates user execution of a potentially malicious file.

attacks.description: Downloads and executes a script using curl and bash
attacks.expected_behavior: The command downloads a script and pipes it to bash for execution. This demonstrates user execution of a potentially malicious script.

attacks.description: Creates a file with a malicious payload, makes it executable, and runs it
attacks.expected_behavior: The command creates a file, adds a benign 'malicious payload' string to it, changes its permissions to executable, and then executes it. This demonstrates user execution of a potentially malicious file in a controlled manner.
